2.

(a)- Empirical risk associated with the 0-1 loss : $\hat{R}(\theta) = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}1_{f_\theta(x_i)\neq y_i}$

True risk associated with the 0-1 loss : $R(\theta) = E(1_{f_\theta(X)\neq Y})$

In this case, the empirical risk is complicated to minimize because it is not differentiable, and hence we cannot use the classical iterative approaches like gradient descient, neither can we easily find a normal solution (if it exists)

(b)- Test data should be used to assess performance, that's because it is new data for the model, and hence it will give us an expectation of how the model would behave on data he wasn't trained on

(c)- The optimization problem associated with :

  • Linear Least Square Regression: $$ min_{\theta} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(f_\theta(x_i)-y_i)^2$$

    where $f_\theta(x_i) = \theta^Tx_i$

  • Linear Logistic Regression: $$ min_{\theta} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} log(1 + e^{-y_i \;f_\theta(x_i)} )$$

    where $f_\theta(x_i) =\theta^Tx_i$

Note : In the models above, we have added a fake feature to our observations $x_i$,as follow : $$\forall i \in [1,n] \;\ x_i^{(0)} = 1$$

(d)- Under the logistic model : $$ P(Y=1|X) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-\theta^TX}}$$

(e)- Link between logistic regression and maximum likelihood estimation:

We know that under the logistic model :

$\forall i \in [1,n]$

  • $ p(y_i = 1|x_i ; \theta) =\frac{1}{1+e^{-\theta^TX}} = \sigma ( \theta^Tx_i) $
  • $ p(y_i = -1|x_i ; \theta) = \frac{1}{1+e^{\theta^TX}} = \sigma (- \theta^Tx_i)$

Which is equivalent to : $\forall i \in [1,n]$ $ p(y_i|x_i ; \theta) = \sigma(y_i \theta^Tx_i) $

The Likelihood function's expression is : $$L(\theta) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} p(y_i|x_i;\theta) = \prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{1+e^{-y_i\theta^TX}} $$

Which gives us the loglikelihood expression : $$ log(L(\theta)) = -\sum_{i=1}^{n} log(1+e^{-y_i\theta^TX})$$

Then : $$argmax_\theta \; logL(\theta) = argmin_\theta \hat{R}(\theta)$$

We have therefore derived the expression of the Logistic Loss from the MLE(maximum likelihood estimator)

Practical reasons behind the use of log likelihood function

  • The likelihood function is expressed at the product of functions,however the product of functions is hard to differentiate, and that's why we use the log likelihood as it is expressed as the sum of functions.
  • Since the $log(x)$ is a monotonically increasing function, we have $argmax_\theta log(L(\theta)) = argmax_\theta(L(\theta))$
  • We also notice, that the use of log likelihood function gave us a probabilistic interpretation of the Logistic Loss (Binary Cross Entropy)

(4)- SGD rule for:

(a)- Linear least-squares regression
$$\forall k \in [0,d] \; \theta_k \leftarrow \theta_k - 2\eta (f_\theta(x_i) - y_i)x_i^{(k)}$$ 
where
$$f_\theta(x_i) = \theta^Tx_i$$ 
(b)- Logistic regression
$$\forall k \in [0,d] \; \theta_k \leftarrow \theta_k + \eta \;(y_i \; \sigma (-y_i\;f_\theta(x_i)))x_i^{(k)}$$ 
where
$$\sigma(-y_i\;f_\theta(x_i)) = \frac{1}{1+e^{y_i\;f_\theta(x_i)}}$$ 
(c)- The perceptron learning algorithm
$$\forall k \in [0,d] \; \theta_k \leftarrow \theta_k - \eta (g(f_\theta(x_i)) - y_i)x_i^{(k)}$$ 
where
$$g(f_\theta(x_i)) = 1 \;\;if\;\; \theta^Tx_i \geq 0 \;\;and \:\:0\;\; if\;\; \theta^Tx_i < 0$$

(6) - K Nearest Neighbors (KNN)¶

(a) - *Definition n of the k-nearest neighbors classification rule with $l2$ metric*

In contrary to Linear Regression, Logistic Regression and the Pereptron, which are based on Risk Minimization, KNN is a method based on local averaging. In fact, for a new input $x \in R^d$, the algorithm looks at the $k$ nearest points $x_i$ in the data set, and uses a majority vote among them

(8)- Results of the models:

Comment on the results :

  • The best algorithm for our classification problem is MLP with a test error of 0.038, which is expected thanks to its ability to model non-linear relationships, which is not the case for GLMs (General Linear Models) like Logistic Regression, Linear Regression and the Perceptron Algorithm.
  • The least performing algorithm is OLS, with a test error of 0.132, which was expected since Linear Regression was designed for regression problems, and not classification ones, and is easily affected by noise, in other words, in classification problems, Linear Regression is easily prone to overfitting

(9)- Why is it important to regularize ?¶

Regularization takes into account the trade-off between Learning and Overfitting, in other words, it founds the right balancing between the bias and the variance of a model. Regularization thus, discourages learning a complex model in order to avoid overfitting.

(9.a)- SGD rule for the three models using $l2$ regularization ?¶

Logistic Regression

$$ \forall k \in [0, d] \;\; \theta_{k+1} \leftarrow (1-2 \lambda \eta)\theta_k+ \eta \;(y_i \; \sigma (-y_i\;f_\theta(x_i)))x_i^{(k)}$$
$$ where \;\; f_\theta(x) = \theta^Tx$$

Linear Least Squares Regression

$$ \forall k \in [0, d] \;\; \theta_{k+1} \leftarrow (1-2 \lambda \eta)\theta_k- 2 \eta(f_\theta(x) -y)x^{(k)}$$

$$ where \;\; f_\theta(x) = \theta^T x$$

Perceptron

$$ \forall k \in [0, d] \;\; \theta_{k+1} \leftarrow (1-2 \lambda \eta)\theta_k- \eta(f_\theta(x) -y)x^{(k)}$$
$$where f_\theta(x) = 1 \;\;if\;\; \theta^Tx \geq 0 \;\;and \:\:0\;\; if\;\; \theta^Tx < 0$$

(9.b)- SGD Updates for the three models using $l1$ regularization ?¶

Logistic Regression

$$ \forall k \in [0, d] \;\; \theta_{k+1} \leftarrow \theta_k - \eta \lambda sgn(\theta_k) + \eta y \sigma(-y\theta^Tx) x_k$$
$$ where \;\; \sigma(x) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}$$

Linear Least Squares Regression

$$ \forall k \in [0, d] \;\; \theta_{k+1} \leftarrow \theta_k - \eta \lambda sgn(\theta_k) - 2 \eta(f_\theta(x) -y)x^{(k)}$$

$$ where \;\; f_\theta(x) = \theta^T x$$

Perceptron

$$ \forall k \in [0, d] \;\; \theta_{k+1} \leftarrow \theta_k - \eta \lambda sgn(\theta_k) - \eta(f_\theta(x) -y)x^{(k)}$$
$$where f_\theta(x) = 1 \;\;if\;\; \theta^Tx \geq 0 \;\;and \:\:0\;\; if\;\; \theta^Tx < 0$$
